n Condensed Matter Physics\n*Recipient, 2006 Honorary Doctor of Science degree from [[Amherst College]].\n*Recipient, 2020 APS Medal for Exceptional Achievement in Research <REF NAME=\"APSPRIZE\">[https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/prizes/prizerecipient.cfm?last_nm=Sarachik&first_nm=Myriam&year=2020 \"2020 APS Medal for Exceptional Achievement in Research Recipient : Myriam Sarachik\"]. American Physical Society, 2019</ref>\n\n==Career==\nThroughout her career Sarachik has held the following positions:<ref name=cwp/>\n*1954-55 Research Assistant, IBM Watson Laboratories, Columbia University\n*1960-61 Research Associate, IBM Watson Laboratories, Columbia University; and Instructor, City College, City University of New York\n*1962-64 Member, Technical Staff, Bell Telephone Laboratories, Murray Hill, NJ\n*1965-67 Assistant Professor, City College, City University of New York\n*1967-71 Associate Professor, City College, City University of New York\n*1971\u2013present Professor, City College, City University of New York\n*1975-78 Executive Officer, CUNY Ph.D. Program in Physics\n*1995\u2013present Distinguished Professor, City College, City University of New York\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100615094724/http://www.sci.ccny.cuny.edu/%7Esarachik/links.html CUNY Low Temperature Group bio]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100615170245/http://www.sci.ccny.cuny.edu/%7Esarachik/trieste.pdf Why Physics?] by Myriam P. Sarachik\n\n{{Presidents of the American Physical Society}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarachik, Myriam}}\n[[Category:1933 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women physicists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Physical Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:L'Or\u00e9al-UNESCO Awards for Women in Science laureates]]\n[[Category:Oliver E. Buckley Condensed Matter Prize winners]]\n[[Category:21st-century physicists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:American women scientistsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myriam_Sarachik"}
{"title_page": "Omowunmi Sadik", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian professor, chemist, and inventor}}\n{{Infobox scientist \n|name              = Omowunmi Sadik\n|image             = Omowunmi Sadik Speaker at Innovation Day 2010backlit.jpg\n|image_size        = 150\n|caption           =\n|birth_name        =\n|birth_date        = 1964\n|birth_place       = [[Lagos, Nigeria]]\n|nationality       = Nigerian\n|field             = [[Surface chemistry]], Environmental nanotechnology\n|work_institutions = [[Binghamton University]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Lagos]], [[Wollongong University]]\n}}\n'''Omowunmi \"Wunmi\" A. Sadik''' (born 19 June 1964) is a Nigerian professor, chemist, and inventor working at [[Binghamton University]]. She has developed microelectrode biosensors for detection of drugs and explosives and is working on the development of technologies for recycling metal ions from waste, for use in environmental and industrial applications. In 2012, Sadik co-founded the non-profit Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSadik was born in 1964 in [[Lagos, Nigeria]]. Her family included a number of scientists, who supported her interests in physics, chemistry, and biology. She received her bachelor's degree in chemistry from the [[University of Lagos]] in 1985, and went on to receive her master's degree in chemistry in 1987. Sadik then attended [[Wollongong University]] in Australia. In 1994, she received her Ph.D. degree in chemistry from Wollongong.<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\">{{cite web|title=ScienceMakers : Omowunmi Sadik|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/omowunmi-sadik|website=The History Makers|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA postdoctoral fellowship from the [[National Research Council (United States)|National Research Council]] supported her as a researcher at the [[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] from 1994 to 1996.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She then accepted a position as an assistant professor of chemistry at the [[Binghamton University]] in [[Binghamton, New York]]. She was promoted to associate professor in 2002, and full professor in 2005. At that time, she also became director of the Center for Advanced Sensors & Environmental Systems (CASE) at Binghamton. She has been visiting faculty at the [[United States Naval Research Laboratory|Naval Research Laboratories]], [[Cornell University]], and [[Harvard University]].<ref name=HistoryMakers/>\n\nSadik studies [[surface chemistry]], with particular emphasis on the development of biosensors for use in environmental chemistry.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She has found that conducting polymers are especially promising for use in sensing applications.<ref name=Bioaffinity>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|title=Bioaffinity Sensors Based on Conducting Polymers: A Short Review|journal=Electroanalysis|date=August 1999|volume=11|issue=12|pages=839\u2013844|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1521-4109(199908)11:12<839::AID-ELAN839>3.0.CO;2-1}}</ref><ref name=polymers>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|last2=Brenda|first2=Sharin|last3=Joasil|first3=Patrick|last4=Lord|first4=John|title=Electropolymerized Conducting Polymers as Glucose Sensors|journal=Journal of Chemical Education|date=July 1999|volume=76|issue=7|pages=967|doi=10.1021/ed076p967|bibcode=1999JChEd..76..967S}}</ref>  She has developed microelectrode biosensors sensitive to trace amounts of organic materials,<ref name=Spotlight>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|title=JEM Spotlight: Applications of advanced nanomaterials for environmental monitoring|journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring|date=2009|volume=11|issue=1|pages=25\u201326|doi=10.1039/B820365M|pmid=19137135}}</ref> technology which can be used for drug and bomb detection.<ref name=Discover-e>{{cite web|title=Sadik invited to give talk at NSF biochemical terrorism workshop|url=https://discovere.binghamton.edu/news/sadik-invited-to-give-talk-at-nsf-biochemical-terrorism-workshop-438.html|website=Discover-e|date=December 7, 2001}}</ref><ref name=Bomb>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=O. A.|last2=Zhou|first2=A. L.|last3=Kikandi|first3=S.|last4=Du|first4=N.|last5=Wang|first5=Q.|last6=Varner|first6=K.|title=Sensors as tools for quantitation, nanotoxicity and nanomonitoring assessment of engineered nanomaterials|journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring|date=2009|volume=11|issue=10|pages=1782\u2013800|doi=10.1039/b912860c|pmid=19809701}}</ref> She is also studying detoxification mechanisms of wastes such as [[Organochloride|organochlorine compounds]] in the environment, with the purpose of developing technologies for recycling metal ions from industrial and environmental waste.<ref name=Binghamton/> In one project, microbial enzymes increased the conversion of highly toxic [[Hexavalent chromium|chromium (VI)]] to non-toxic chromium (III) from 40% to 98%.<ref name=Farrington>{{cite journal|last1=Farrington|first1=Keith|title=Interview: Monitoring the environment|journal=Highlights in Chemical Technology|date=4 March 2010|volume=Royal Society of Chemistry|url=http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/ChemTech/Volume/2010/03/omowunmi_sadik_interview.asp|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> Sadik is credited with more than 135 peer-reviewed research papers and patent applications. She holds U.S. patents on particular types of biosensors.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> In 2011, she was the chair of the inaugural Gordon Conference on Environmental Nanotechnology.<ref name=Nano.gov>{{cite web|title=Omowunmi Sadik, SUNY-Binghamton : Nano|url=http://www.nano.gov/Sadik|website=National Nanotechnology Initiative|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Sadik and [[Barbara Karn]] co-founded the Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization, a non-profit, international professional society for the responsible use of nanotechnology worldwide.<ref name=SNO>{{cite web|last1=SNO Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization|title=First Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization Conference Program|url=http://www.susnano.org/images/SNO_Program2012.pdf|website=SNO Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization|date=November 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSadik is an elected fellow of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (2010) and of the [[American Institute for Medical and Biological Engineering]] (elected 2012). She is also a member of the [[American Chemical Society]].  She is involved with the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[National Science Foundation]], and was part of the [[National Institutes of Health]] Study Panel on Instrumentation and Systems Development.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She is involved in international collaborations with the [[UNESCO]] International Center of Biodynamics in [[Bucharest]], Romania, [[Ege University]] in Turkey, and the [[University of Fukui]] in Japan.<ref name=Binghamton/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2000, National Research Council (NRC) COBASE fellowship<ref name=SUNYBio>{{cite web|title=Omowunmi \"Wunmi\" Sadik|url=http://chemiris.chem.binghamton.edu/SADIK/sadik.htm|website=Department of Chemistry, State University of New York at Binghamton|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2001, Chancellor's Award for Research in Science and Medicine, SUNY<ref name=Binghamton>{{cite web|title=Faculty Spotlight: OMOWUNMI SADIK, Ph.D. ASSISTANT PROFESSOR, ANALYTICAL & ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMISTRY|url=http://research.binghamton.edu/faculty/SADIK/sadik.htm|website=Binghamton University|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2002, Chancellor's Award for Premier Inventors, SUNY<ref name=Binghamton/>\n* 2003\u20132004, Distinguished Radcliffe Fellowship from Harvard University<ref name=Radcliffe>{{cite web|title=Fellow: Omowunmi A.Sadik|url=https://www.radcliffe.harvard.edu/people/omowunmi-sadik|website=Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study Harvard University|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2005\u20132006, NSF Discovery Corps Senior Fellowship<ref name=NSF2005>{{cite web|title=NSF Announces New Discovery Corps Fellows|url=https://www.nsf.gov/mobile/news/news_summ.jsp?cntn_id=104365&org=MPS|website=National Science Foundation|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Nigerian National Order of Merit Award]] (NNOM)<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.binghamton.edu/inside/index.php/inside/story/16999/sadik-honored-with-nigerian-national-order-of-merit/ | title= Sadik honored with Nigerian National Order of Merit Kudu  | author = Katie Ellis | date = 17 January 2017| accessdate= 29 July 2017 | publisher= Binghamton University, State University of New York}}</ref><ref name=\"Idoko\">{{cite news |last1=Idoko |first1=Clement |title=FG names Professors Omowunmi, Ojaide 2016 winners of NNOM award |url=https://www.tribuneonlineng.com/43152/ |accessdate=28 December 2018 |work=Nigerian Tribune |date=November 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017, Jefferson Science Fellow<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sites.nationalacademies.org/PGA/Jefferson/PGA_046613| title= 2017 Jefferson Science Fellow  | author = | date = 2017| accessdate= 29 July 2017 | publisher= The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine}}</ref>\n* Australian Merit Award<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadik, Omowunmi}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lagos]]\n[[Category:University of Lagos alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Wollongong alumni]]\n[[Category:Nigerian chemists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the African Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women chemists]]\n[[Category:Binghamton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women academics]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women academics]]\n[[Category:Yoruba scientists]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Nigerian inventors]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:State University of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Inventors]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe fellows]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:Women inventors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute for Medical and Biological Engineering]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Lagos]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian professor, chemist, and inventor}}\n{{Infobox scientist \n|name              = Omowunmi Sadik\n|image             = Omowunmi Sadik Speaker at Innovation Day 2010backlit.jpg\n|image_size        = 150\n|caption           =\n|birth_name        =\n|birth_date        = 1964\n|birth_place       = [[Lagos, Nigeria]]\n|nationality       = Nigerian\n|field             = [[Surface chemistry]], Environmental nanotechnology\n|work_institutions = [[Binghamton University]]\n|alma_mater        = [[University of Lagos]], [[Wollongong University]]\n}}\n'''Omowunmi \"Wunmi\" A. Sadik''' (born 19 June 1964) is a Nigerian professor, chemist, and inventor working at [[Binghamton University]]. She has developed microelectrode biosensors for detection of drugs and explosives and is working on the development of technologies for recycling metal ions from waste, for use in environmental and industrial applications. In 2012, Sadik co-founded the non-profit Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization.\n\n==Early life and education==\nSadik was born in 1964 in [[Lagos, Nigeria]]. Her family included a number of scientists, who supported her interests in physics, chemistry, and biology. She received her bachelor's degree in chemistry from the [[University of Lagos]] in 1985, and went on to receive her master's degree in chemistry in 1987. Sadik then attended [[Wollongong University]] in Australia. In 1994, she received her Ph.D. degree in chemistry from Wollongong.<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\">{{cite web|title=ScienceMakers : Omowunmi Sadik|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/omowunmi-sadik|website=The History Makers|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nA postdoctoral fellowship from the [[National Research Council (United States)|National Research Council]] supported her as a researcher at the [[U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]] from 1994 to 1996.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She then accepted a position as an assistant professor of chemistry at the [[Binghamton University]] in [[Binghamton, New York]]. She was promoted to associate professor in 2002, and full professor in 2005. At that time, she also became director of the Center for Advanced Sensors & Environmental Systems (CASE) at Binghamton. She has been visiting faculty at the [[United States Naval Research Laboratory|Naval Research Laboratories]], [[Cornell University]], and [[Harvard University]].<ref name=HistoryMakers/>\n\nSadik studies [[surface chemistry]], with particular emphasis on the development of biosensors for use in environmental chemistry.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She has found that conducting polymers are especially promising for use in sensing applications.<ref name=Bioaffinity>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|title=Bioaffinity Sensors Based on Conducting Polymers: A Short Review|journal=Electroanalysis|date=August 1999|volume=11|issue=12|pages=839\u2013844|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1521-4109(199908)11:12<839::AID-ELAN839>3.0.CO;2-1}}</ref><ref name=polymers>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|last2=Brenda|first2=Sharin|last3=Joasil|first3=Patrick|last4=Lord|first4=John|title=Electropolymerized Conducting Polymers as Glucose Sensors|journal=Journal of Chemical Education|date=July 1999|volume=76|issue=7|pages=967|doi=10.1021/ed076p967|bibcode=1999JChEd..76..967S}}</ref>  She has developed microelectrode biosensors sensitive to trace amounts of organic materials,<ref name=Spotlight>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=Omowunmi A.|title=JEM Spotlight: Applications of advanced nanomaterials for environmental monitoring|journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring|date=2009|volume=11|issue=1|pages=25\u201326|doi=10.1039/B820365M|pmid=19137135}}</ref> technology which can be used for drug and bomb detection.<ref name=Discover-e>{{cite web|title=Sadik invited to give talk at NSF biochemical terrorism workshop|url=https://discovere.binghamton.edu/news/sadik-invited-to-give-talk-at-nsf-biochemical-terrorism-workshop-438.html|website=Discover-e|date=December 7, 2001}}</ref><ref name=Bomb>{{cite journal|last1=Sadik|first1=O. A.|last2=Zhou|first2=A. L.|last3=Kikandi|first3=S.|last4=Du|first4=N.|last5=Wang|first5=Q.|last6=Varner|first6=K.|title=Sensors as tools for quantitation, nanotoxicity and nanomonitoring assessment of engineered nanomaterials|journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring|date=2009|volume=11|issue=10|pages=1782\u2013800|doi=10.1039/b912860c|pmid=19809701}}</ref> She is also studying detoxification mechanisms of wastes such as [[Organochloride|organochlorine compounds]] in the environment, with the purpose of developing technologies for recycling metal ions from industrial and environmental waste.<ref name=Binghamton/> In one project, microbial enzymes increased the conversion of highly toxic [[Hexavalent chromium|chromium (VI)]] to non-toxic chromium (III) from 40% to 98%.<ref name=Farrington>{{cite journal|last1=Farrington|first1=Keith|title=Interview: Monitoring the environment|journal=Highlights in Chemical Technology|date=4 March 2010|volume=Royal Society of Chemistry|url=http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/ChemTech/Volume/2010/03/omowunmi_sadik_interview.asp|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> Sadik is credited with more than 135 peer-reviewed research papers and patent applications. She holds U.S. patents on particular types of biosensors.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> In 2011, she was the chair of the inaugural Gordon Conference on Environmental Nanotechnology.<ref name=Nano.gov>{{cite web|title=Omowunmi Sadik, SUNY-Binghamton : Nano|url=http://www.nano.gov/Sadik|website=National Nanotechnology Initiative|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Sadik and [[Barbara Karn]] co-founded the Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization, a non-profit, international professional society for the responsible use of nanotechnology worldwide.<ref name=SNO>{{cite web|last1=SNO Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization|title=First Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization Conference Program|url=http://www.susnano.org/images/SNO_Program2012.pdf|website=SNO Sustainable Nanotechnology Organization|date=November 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSadik is an elected fellow of the [[Royal Society of Chemistry]] (2010) and of the [[American Institute for Medical and Biological Engineering]] (elected 2012). She is also a member of the [[American Chemical Society]].  She is involved with the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] and the [[National Science Foundation]], and was part of the [[National Institutes of Health]] Study Panel on Instrumentation and Systems Development.<ref name=HistoryMakers/> She is involved in international collaborations with the [[UNESCO]] International Center of Biodynamics in [[Bucharest]], Romania, [[Ege University]] in Turkey, and the [[University of Fukui]] in Japan.<ref name=Binghamton/>\n\n==Awards==\n\n* 2000, National Research Council (NRC) COBASE fellowship<ref name=SUNYBio>{{cite web|title=Omowunmi \"Wunmi\" Sadik|url=http://chemiris.chem.binghamton.edu/SADIK/sadik.htm|website=Department of Chemistry, State University of New York at Binghamton|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2001, Chancellor's Award for Research in Science and Medicine, SUNY<ref name=Binghamton>{{cite web|title=Faculty Spotlight: OMOWUNMI SADIK, Ph.D. ASSISTANT PROFESSOR, ANALYTICAL & ENVIRONMENTAL CHEMISTRY|url=http://research.binghamton.edu/faculty/SADIK/sadik.htm|website=Binghamton University|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2002, Chancellor's Award for Premier Inventors, SUNY<ref name=Binghamton/>\n* 2003\u20132004, Distinguished Radcliffe Fellowship from Harvard University<ref name=Radcliffe>{{cite web|title=Fellow: Omowunmi A.Sadik|url=https://www.radcliffe.harvard.edu/people/omowunmi-sadik|website=Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study Harvard University|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2005\u20132006, NSF Discovery Corps Senior Fellowship<ref name=NSF2005>{{cite web|title=NSF Announces New Discovery Corps Fellows|url=https://www.nsf.gov/mobile/news/news_summ.jsp?cntn_id=104365&org=MPS|website=National Science Foundation|accessdate=13 November 2015}}</ref>\n* 2016, [[Nigerian National Order of Merit Award]] (NNOM)<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.binghamton.edu/inside/index.php/inside/story/16999/sadik-honored-with-nigerian-national-order-of-merit/ | title= Sadik honored with Nigerian National Order of Merit Kudu  | author = Katie Ellis | date = 17 January 2017| accessdate= 29 July 2017 | publisher= Binghamton University, State University of New York}}</ref><ref name=\"Idoko\">{{cite news |last1=Idoko |first1=Clement |title=FG names Professors Omowunmi, Ojaide 2016 winners of NNOM award |url=https://www.tribuneonlineng.com/43152/ |accessdate=28 December 2018 |work=Nigerian Tribune |date=November 25, 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017, Jefferson Science Fellow<ref>{{cite web |url= http://sites.nationalacademies.org/PGA/Jefferson/PGA_046613| title= 2017 Jefferson Science Fellow  | author = | date = 2017| accessdate= 29 July 2017 | publisher= The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine}}</ref>\n* Australian Merit Award<ref name=\"HistoryMakers\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadik, Omowunmi}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Lagos]]\n[[Category:University of Lagos alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Wollongong alumni]]\n[[Category:Nigerian chemists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the African Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society of Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women chemists]]\n[[Category:Binghamton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yoruba women academics]]\n[[Category:Nigerian women academics]]\n[[Category:Yoruba scientists]]\n[[Category:American people of Nigerian descent]]\n[[Category:Nigerian inventors]]\n[[Category:American people of Yoruba descent]]\n[[Category:State University of New York faculty]]\n[[Category:Nigerian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Inventors]]\n[[Category:Radcliffe fellows]]\n[[Category:American women academics]]\n[[Category:Women inventors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Institute for Medical and Biological Engineering]]\n[[Category:21st-century American inventors]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Lagos]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:American women scientistsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Omowunmi_Sadik"}
{"title_page": "Kathy Reichs", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Reichs||Reich (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American writer and forensic anthropologist}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = KathyReichs september2013.jpg\n| honorific-suffix={{post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| imagesize   = \n| name        = Kathy Reichs\n| caption     = Reichs in 2013\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1948|07|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.<ref name=EB/>\n| occupation  = [[forensic anthropologist|Forensic Anthropologist]]<br>[[Novelist]]<br>[[Professor]]<ref name=EB/>\n| nationality =  American\n| genre       = [[Crime]]\n| movement    =\n| notableworks = ''[[Break No Bones (novel)|Break No Bones]]'' <small> (2006)<ref name=EB/></small>\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.kathyreichs.com}}\n}}\n'''Kathleen Joan Toelle Reichs''' (born July 7, 1948<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2007-Pu-Z/Reichs-Kathleen-J.html|title=Kathleen J. Reichs Biography|work=notablebiographies.com}}</ref>) is an American [[crime writer]], [[forensic anthropologist]] and [[academic]].<ref name=EB/> She is an adjunct professor of [[anthropology]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]; {{As of|2016|lc=y}} she is on indefinite leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://inside.uncc.edu/news-features/2016-02-01/reichs-among-%E2%80%9930-most-innovative-women-professors%E2%80%99|title=Reichs among '30 Most Innovative Women Professors'|last=|first=|date=February 1, 2016|website=|publisher=UNC Charlotte|access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref> She is also affiliated with the ''Laboratoire des Sciences Judiciaires et de M\u00e9decine L\u00e9gale'' for the [[province]] of [[Quebec]]. She is one of 100 anthropologists certified by the American Board of Forensic Anthropology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theabfa.org/diplomates.html |title=ABFA - American Board of Forensic Anthropology |work=theabfa.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007074500/http://www.theabfa.org/diplomates.html |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> and is on the Board of Directors of the [[American Academy of Forensic Sciences]]. Her schedule also involves a number of speaking engagements around the world. Reichs was a producer for the TV series [[Bones (TV series)|''Bones'']], which is loosely based on her novels, which in turn, are inspired by her life.<ref name=\"EB\">\"Reichs, Kathy\", Britannica Online (''see below:'' References).</ref> She has two daughters, Kerry and Courtney, and one son, Brendan.<ref name=Acknowledgements>{{cite book|last=Reichs|first=Kathy|title=Grave Secrets: A Novel|year=2002|publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.|isbn=978-0-671-02838-1|pages=XII|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/gravesecrets00reic}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nReichs earned her [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree with a major in [[anthropology]] from [[American University]] in 1971. In 1972, she completed her [[Master of Arts]] in [[physical anthropology]] from [[Northwestern University]], and in 1975 she completed her [[Ph.D.]] in physical anthropology from Northwestern University. Since then, Reichs has taught at [[Northern Illinois University]], [[University of Pittsburgh]], [[Concordia University (Quebec)|Concordia University]], and [[McGill University]], and is currently on leave from a position as adjunct professor of anthropology at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]. In the past, Kathy Reichs has consulted for the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathyreichs.com/about-kathy/|title=Kathy Reichs - About Kathy|work=kathyreichs.com}}</ref>\n\nReichs has appeared in Tanzania to testify at the [[United Nations]]'s [[International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmagazine.com/issues/2007/august/interview-reichs.php|title=History, Travel, Arts, Science, People, Places - Smithsonian|work=smithsonianmagazine.com}}</ref>  She has assisted Dr. [[Clyde Snow]] and the [[Foundation for Guatemalan Forensic Anthropology]] in an [[exhumation]] in the area of [[Lago de Atitl\u00e1n|Lake Atitlan]] in the highlands of southwest [[Guatemala]].  She was a member of the [[Disaster Mortuary Operational Response Team]] assigned to assist at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center disaster]].\n\n===Academic papers===\n*{{cite journal|title=Quantified comparison of frontal sinus patterns by means of computed tomography|journal=Forensic Science International|date=October 1993|volume=61|issue=2\u20133|pages=141\u201368|doi=10.1016/0379-0738(93)90222-v|pmid=8307523|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Effect of age and osteoarthritis on bone mineral in rhesus monkey vertebrae|journal=Journal of Bone and Mineral Research|publisher=[[American Society for Bone and Mineral Research]]|date=August 1993|volume=8|issue=8|pages=909\u201317|doi=10.1002/jbmr.5650080803|pmid=8213253|last1=Grynpas|first1=Marc D.|last2=Huckell|first2=C.B.|last3=Reichs|first3=K.J.|last4=Derousseau|first4=C.J.|last5=Greenwood|first5=C.|last6=Kessler|first6=M.J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Forensic anthropology in the 1990s|journal=The American Journal of Forensic Medicine and Pathology|date=June 1992|volume=13|issue=2|pages=146\u201353|doi=10.1097/00000433-199206000-00014|pmid=1510066|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Treponematosis: a possible case from the late prehistoric of North Carolina|journal=[[American Journal of Physical Anthropology]]|date=July 1989|volume=79|issue=3|pages=289\u2013303|doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330790305|pmid=2669501|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Cranial suture eccentricities: a case in which precocious closure complicated determination of sex and commingling|journal=Journal of Forensic Sciences|date=January 1989|volume=34|issue=1|pages=263\u201373}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Ontogenetic plasticity in nonhuman primates: I. Secular trends in the Cayo Santiago macaques|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|date=July 1987|volume=73|issue=3|pages=279\u201387|doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330730302|pmid=3618758 | last1 = DeRousseau | first1 = CJ | last2 = Reichs | first2 = KJ}}\n\n===Academic books===\n* {{cite book|title=Forensic Osteology: Advances in the Identification of Human Remains|url=https://archive.org/details/forensicosteolog0000unse|url-access=registration|date=1986|publisher=Charles C. Thomas|location=[[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]]|edition=1st|isbn=9780398068042}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Kathy|editor-last=Reichs|title=Hominid Origins: Inquiries Past and Present|date=1983|publisher=[[University Press of America]]|isbn=9780819128645}}\n\n== Fiction==\nIn addition to [[technical writing|technical books]], as of January 2019 Reichs has written 21 [[novel]]s, which have been translated into 30 languages.  20 of those novels constitute the 'Temperance Brennan' series.<ref>[http://www.kathyreichs.com/suppliers.htm Kathy Reichs book suppliers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914112500/http://www.kathyreichs.com/suppliers.htm |date=2007-09-14 }}. Personal website. Retrieved 1/11/09.</ref> Her first novel, ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead'', won the 1997 [[Arthur Ellis Awards|Arthur Ellis Award]] for Best First Novel.<ref>[http://crimewriterscanada.com/cwc/pages/pastawards.html Arthur Ellis Award - list of past winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928140538/http://crimewriterscanada.com/cwc/pages/pastawards.html |date=2008-09-28 }}. Crime Writers of Canada. Retrieved 1/11/09.</ref>\n\nThe fictional [[hero]]ine in her novels, [[Temperance Brennan|Temperance \"Tempe\" Brennan]], is also a forensic anthropologist.  Her lifestyle closely mimics that of her creator,<ref name=\"birthday\">{{cite news| title =This much I know:Kathy Reichs, forensic anthropologist and writer, 60, London | work =Tom Templeton  | publisher =The Guardian | date =2008-10-26 | url =https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/26/1 }}</ref><ref name=\"bookpage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpage.com/9709bp/firstperson1.html |title=Meet this season's best discovery: Kathy Reichs |accessdate= 2008-11-16 |last=Mudge |first=Alden |date= September 1997 |publisher=Bookpage |archivedate=2008-06-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623094953/http://www.bookpage.com/9709bp/firstperson1.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> with Reichs stating that Brennan and she \"have the same CV\"<ref name=\"birthday\" /> and that \"Some of Tempe's personality traits are also mine\",<ref name= \"bookpage\" /> but there are differences in their personal lives such as the character's [[alcoholism]].<ref name=\"birthday\" />  A good portion of the novels are based on real life science, and Reichs has stated that she is \"fastidiously conscientious about getting the science right\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news| title =Kathy Reichs: The ice queen of crime | work =Peter Stanford | publisher =The Independent | date =2006-07-21 | url =https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/kathy-reichs-the-ice-queen-of-crime-408662.html }}</ref> She has used experience from her career in her novels, and said about ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead'' that \"Everything I describe in the book, I actually did\".<ref name=\"bookpage\" /> In the novel ''Grave Secrets'', she uses her experience from her visit to [[Guatemala]].<ref name= \"independent\" />\n\nShe has also written the [[young adult novel]]s series named ''[[Virals]]'' centered on Tempe's great-niece, Tory Brennan, and a pack of her friends Ben, Hiram, Shelton, and wolfdog Cooper.\n\nHer latest novel, ''Two Nights'', published July 11, 2017, features Sunday Night, a tough-talking, scarred heroine.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Two nights|last=Kathy|first=Reichs|isbn= 9781476726458|location=Toronto|oclc= 960987420|date = 2017-07-11}}</ref>\n\n===Temperance Brennan series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!No.\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBNs\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead]]''\n|1997\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-925518-9}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-449-83348-9}}\n|Won the 1997 [[Arthur Ellis Awards|Arthur Ellis Award]] for Best First Novel\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Death du Jour]]''\n|1999\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-925519-7}}<br />Hardcover: {{ISBNT|0-684-84118-5}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|0-754-05330-X}}\n|\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Deadly Decisions|Deadly D\u00e9cisions]]''\n|2000\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930710-3}}<br />Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-00820-6}}\n|\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Fatal Voyage]]''\n|2001\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930720-0}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-927-X}}\n|\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Grave Secrets]]''\n|2002\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930730-8}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-928-8}}\n|\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Bare Bones (novel)|Bare Bones]]''\n|2003\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944147-0}}\n|\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Monday Mourning]]''\n|2004\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944148-9}}\n|\n|-\n|8\n|''[[Cross Bones (novel)|Cross Bones]]''\n|2005\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944149-7}}<br />Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01040-5}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-985-7}}\n|\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Break No Bones]]''\n|2006\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01042-1}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01544-X}}\n|\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Bones to Ashes]]''\n|2007\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434014620}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1416525653}}\n|\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Devil Bones]]''\n|2008\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0743294386}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1-4391-5440-3}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|978-1846571336}}\n|\n|-\n|12\n|''[[206 Bones]]''\n|2009\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0743294393}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0-4340-2005-8}}<br />\n|\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Spider Bones]]'' \n|2010\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-1439102398}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0-0995-5686-2}}<br />\n|released as ''Mortal Remains'' in UK and Australia in hardback,<br />reverted to ''Spider Bones'' for paperback release\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Flash and Bones]]''\n|2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1439102411}}\n|\n|-\n|15\n|''[[Bones are Forever]]''\n|2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-0434021130}}\n|\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Bones of the Lost]]'' \n|2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1439102459}}\n|\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Bones Never Lie]]''\n|2014\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0345544018}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0804194471}}\n|\n|-\n|18\n|''[[Speaking in Bones]]''\n| 2015\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434021192}}\n|\n|-\n|19\n| ''The Bone Collection''\n| 2016\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|9780606394642}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|9780399593222}}\n| A short story collection including ''First Bones'' (a prequel to ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead''), ''Bones in her Pocket'', ''Swamp Bones'' and ''Bones on Ice''. These books have been numbered as 0.5, 15.5, 16.5, 17.5, respectively.<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28952915-the-bone-collection GoodReads]. GoodReads. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref>\n|-\n|20\n| ''A Conspiracy of Bones''\n| 2020\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|9781785151187}}\n| \n|}\n\n===Stand-alone books===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!No.\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBNs\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n| ''Two Nights''\n|2017\n| Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434021116}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1524755577}}\n| Stand-alone, \"off-series\" novel with new characters.<ref>[https://twitter.com/KathyReichs/status/803957093938167808 Twitter]. Twitter. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref><ref>[http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/books/reading-matters-blog/article111647727.html Website]. Website. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref>\n|}\n\n===Virals series===\n{{main|Virals}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBN\n!Notes\n|-\n|''[[Virals (novel)|Virals]]''\n|2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-0099543947}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Seizure (Reichs novel)|Seizure]]''\n|2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595143945}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Code (Reichs novel)|Code]]''\n|2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-0099543855}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Exposure (Reichs novel)|Exposure]]''\n|2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595145307}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Terminal (Reichs novel)|Terminal]]''\n|2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595145284}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Trace Evidence (Reichs novel)|Trace Evidence]]'' \n|2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1784752392}}\n| a short story collection including ''Shock'', ''Shift'', ''Swipe'' and ''Spike'' (a new story set after the events of ''Terminal'').\n|-\n|}\n\n===Novellas===\nReichs has released six downloadable short stories:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!Title\n!Published\n!Notes\n|-\n|''Shift''\n|2013\n| Set in the ''Virals'' country, but featuring both the Virals characters and Temperance Brennan.\n|-\n|''Bones In Her Pocket''\n|2013\n| A Temperance Brennan story giving details of a case briefly mentioned in ''Bones of the Lost''.\n|-\n|''Swipe''\n|2013\n| A ''Virals'' story, also featuring Temperance Brennan, set at Comic-Con in San Diego.\n|-\n|''Swamp Bones''\n|2014\n| A Temperance Brennan story set in the Florida Everglades.\n|-\n|''Shock''\n|2015\n| A ''Virals'' story telling how they first meet.\n|-\n|''Bones On Ice''\n|2015\n| A Temperance Brennan story of how she gets wrapped up in the ultimate cold case: a death on Mount Everest.\n|}\n\n== Television ==\n{{Main|Bones (TV series)}}\nThe 2005 [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television series [[Bones (TV series)|''Bones'']] is inspired by Reichs' life and writing.<ref name=\"fox\">[http://www.fox.com/bones/showinfo/ Bones Show Info] {{webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070923004209/http://www.fox.com/bones/showinfo/ |date=2007-09-23 }}</ref> The series borrows the name of the books' heroine, [[Temperance Brennan|Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]].<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite web |url=http://au.tv.yahoo.com/b/bones/549/kathy-reichs-20-things-you-need-to-know |title= Kathy Reichs: 20 Things You Need to Know |work=[[Yahoo!]] |publisher=Yahoo! Pty Limited |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728010753/http://au.tv.yahoo.com/b/bones/549/kathy-reichs-20-things-you-need-to-know |archivedate=2008-07-28 |accessdate= 2008-11-16 }}</ref> As in the books, Brennan ([[Emily Deschanel]]) is a forensic anthropologist; however, there are many differences: the television character is younger, more socially awkward,<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> and is based in a fictionalized version of the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> Additionally, the TV-Brennan moonlights as an author,<ref name=\"fox\" /> writing about a fictional forensic anthropologist named Kathy Reichs.<ref>{{cite episode| title =Bodies in the Book | episodelink = | series =Bones | serieslink =Bones (TV series) | airdate =2007-10-14 | season =2 | number =15 }}</ref> Aside from the character name and occupation, there are few tie-ins between the TV show and the books.\n\nReichs works as a producer on the show to \"keep the science honest\".<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> She appeared in the second season episode \"Judas on a Pole\", playing Professor Constance Wright, a forensic anthropologist on the board conducting [[Zack Addy]]'s [[Dissertation#Examination|dissertation defense]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0915947/ ''Bones'' episode ''Judas on a Pole''] at IMDb.com</ref> She wrote the [[Bones (season 5)|Season Five]] episode \"The Witch in the Wardrobe\"<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1613910/fullcredits Full credits for ''Bones'' episode \"The Witch in the Wardrobe\"] at IMDb.com</ref> and the [[Bones (season 9)|Season Nine]] episode \"The Dude in the Dam\" and the [[Bones (season 11)|Season Eleven]] episode  \"The Stiff in the Cliff\" with her daughter Kerry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givememyremote.com/remote/2013/11/12/bones-recap-the-dude-in-the-dam/|title= BONES Recap: 'The Dude in the Dam'|work= givememyremote.com}}</ref>\n\n==Casey Anthony murder trial==\n{{Main|Death of Caylee Anthony}}\nIn 2011, Reichs was an expert witness in the [[Casey Anthony]] murder trial. After initially refusing to be a part of Anthony's defense, she cited biased media coverage as the reason she changed her mind.  \"Initially, I said no, and then I started seeing media coverage and it made me angry. This woman needed to be tried in court, not in the press.\"\n\nReichs performed a full skeletal analysis of Anthony's daughter, Caylee, but could not determine a cause of death.  She concluded that there was no evidence of abuse and that the child appeared to be well-nourished.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/books/news/story/2011-08-22/For-author-Kathy-Reichs-its-all-about-the-bones/50099182/1 | archiveurl= https://archive.is/20130412022818/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/books/news/story/2011-08-22/For-author-Kathy-Reichs-its-all-about-the-bones/50099182/1 | title= Reichs Examines Murder Victim Caylee Anthony | work= [[USA Today]]| archivedate= 12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Reichs, Kathy\", Britannica Online Encyclopedia, 2009, webpage: [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1377721/Kathy-Reichs EBc-KReichs].\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kathy Reichs}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kathyreichs.com}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121210061409/http://www.jarrahloh.com/kathy-reichs/ Kathy Reichs: Turning a lifelong career into writing success] at Jarrah Loh.com\n*[http://www.shotsmag.co.uk/interview_view.aspx?interview_id=250 Kathy Reichs Interview Shots Ezine October 2012]\n\n{{Kathy Reichs}}\n{{Bones}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reichs, Kathy}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American forensic scientists]]\n[[Category:American academics]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:Forensic anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Women forensic scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Bones (TV series)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Reichs||Reich (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American writer and forensic anthropologist}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| image       = KathyReichs september2013.jpg\n| honorific-suffix={{post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}}\n| imagesize   = \n| name        = Kathy Reichs\n| caption     = Reichs in 2013\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1948|07|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.<ref name=EB/>\n| occupation  = [[forensic anthropologist|Forensic Anthropologist]]<br>[[Novelist]]<br>[[Professor]]<ref name=EB/>\n| nationality =  American\n| genre       = [[Crime]]\n| movement    =\n| notableworks = ''[[Break No Bones (novel)|Break No Bones]]'' <small> (2006)<ref name=EB/></small>\n| influences  =\n| influenced  =\n| website     = {{URL|http://www.kathyreichs.com}}\n}}\n'''Kathleen Joan Toelle Reichs''' (born July 7, 1948<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/newsmakers2/2007-Pu-Z/Reichs-Kathleen-J.html|title=Kathleen J. Reichs Biography|work=notablebiographies.com}}</ref>) is an American [[crime writer]], [[forensic anthropologist]] and [[academic]].<ref name=EB/> She is an adjunct professor of [[anthropology]] at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]; {{As of|2016|lc=y}} she is on indefinite leave.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://inside.uncc.edu/news-features/2016-02-01/reichs-among-%E2%80%9930-most-innovative-women-professors%E2%80%99|title=Reichs among '30 Most Innovative Women Professors'|last=|first=|date=February 1, 2016|website=|publisher=UNC Charlotte|access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref> She is also affiliated with the ''Laboratoire des Sciences Judiciaires et de M\u00e9decine L\u00e9gale'' for the [[province]] of [[Quebec]]. She is one of 100 anthropologists certified by the American Board of Forensic Anthropology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theabfa.org/diplomates.html |title=ABFA - American Board of Forensic Anthropology |work=theabfa.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007074500/http://www.theabfa.org/diplomates.html |archivedate=2011-10-07 }}</ref> and is on the Board of Directors of the [[American Academy of Forensic Sciences]]. Her schedule also involves a number of speaking engagements around the world. Reichs was a producer for the TV series [[Bones (TV series)|''Bones'']], which is loosely based on her novels, which in turn, are inspired by her life.<ref name=\"EB\">\"Reichs, Kathy\", Britannica Online (''see below:'' References).</ref> She has two daughters, Kerry and Courtney, and one son, Brendan.<ref name=Acknowledgements>{{cite book|last=Reichs|first=Kathy|title=Grave Secrets: A Novel|year=2002|publisher=Simon & Schuster, Inc.|isbn=978-0-671-02838-1|pages=XII|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/gravesecrets00reic}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nReichs earned her [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree with a major in [[anthropology]] from [[American University]] in 1971. In 1972, she completed her [[Master of Arts]] in [[physical anthropology]] from [[Northwestern University]], and in 1975 she completed her [[Ph.D.]] in physical anthropology from Northwestern University. Since then, Reichs has taught at [[Northern Illinois University]], [[University of Pittsburgh]], [[Concordia University (Quebec)|Concordia University]], and [[McGill University]], and is currently on leave from a position as adjunct professor of anthropology at the [[University of North Carolina at Charlotte]]. In the past, Kathy Reichs has consulted for the Office of the Chief Medical Examiner in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kathyreichs.com/about-kathy/|title=Kathy Reichs - About Kathy|work=kathyreichs.com}}</ref>\n\nReichs has appeared in Tanzania to testify at the [[United Nations]]'s [[International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmagazine.com/issues/2007/august/interview-reichs.php|title=History, Travel, Arts, Science, People, Places - Smithsonian|work=smithsonianmagazine.com}}</ref>  She has assisted Dr. [[Clyde Snow]] and the [[Foundation for Guatemalan Forensic Anthropology]] in an [[exhumation]] in the area of [[Lago de Atitl\u00e1n|Lake Atitlan]] in the highlands of southwest [[Guatemala]].  She was a member of the [[Disaster Mortuary Operational Response Team]] assigned to assist at the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center disaster]].\n\n===Academic papers===\n*{{cite journal|title=Quantified comparison of frontal sinus patterns by means of computed tomography|journal=Forensic Science International|date=October 1993|volume=61|issue=2\u20133|pages=141\u201368|doi=10.1016/0379-0738(93)90222-v|pmid=8307523|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Effect of age and osteoarthritis on bone mineral in rhesus monkey vertebrae|journal=Journal of Bone and Mineral Research|publisher=[[American Society for Bone and Mineral Research]]|date=August 1993|volume=8|issue=8|pages=909\u201317|doi=10.1002/jbmr.5650080803|pmid=8213253|last1=Grynpas|first1=Marc D.|last2=Huckell|first2=C.B.|last3=Reichs|first3=K.J.|last4=Derousseau|first4=C.J.|last5=Greenwood|first5=C.|last6=Kessler|first6=M.J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Forensic anthropology in the 1990s|journal=The American Journal of Forensic Medicine and Pathology|date=June 1992|volume=13|issue=2|pages=146\u201353|doi=10.1097/00000433-199206000-00014|pmid=1510066|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Treponematosis: a possible case from the late prehistoric of North Carolina|journal=[[American Journal of Physical Anthropology]]|date=July 1989|volume=79|issue=3|pages=289\u2013303|doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330790305|pmid=2669501|last1=Reichs|first1=Kathleen J.}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Cranial suture eccentricities: a case in which precocious closure complicated determination of sex and commingling|journal=Journal of Forensic Sciences|date=January 1989|volume=34|issue=1|pages=263\u201373}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Ontogenetic plasticity in nonhuman primates: I. Secular trends in the Cayo Santiago macaques|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|date=July 1987|volume=73|issue=3|pages=279\u201387|doi=10.1002/ajpa.1330730302|pmid=3618758 | last1 = DeRousseau | first1 = CJ | last2 = Reichs | first2 = KJ}}\n\n===Academic books===\n* {{cite book|title=Forensic Osteology: Advances in the Identification of Human Remains|url=https://archive.org/details/forensicosteolog0000unse|url-access=registration|date=1986|publisher=Charles C. Thomas|location=[[Springfield, Illinois|Springfield]]|edition=1st|isbn=9780398068042}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Kathy|editor-last=Reichs|title=Hominid Origins: Inquiries Past and Present|date=1983|publisher=[[University Press of America]]|isbn=9780819128645}}\n\n== Fiction==\nIn addition to [[technical writing|technical books]], as of January 2019 Reichs has written 21 [[novel]]s, which have been translated into 30 languages.  20 of those novels constitute the 'Temperance Brennan' series.<ref>[http://www.kathyreichs.com/suppliers.htm Kathy Reichs book suppliers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070914112500/http://www.kathyreichs.com/suppliers.htm |date=2007-09-14 }}. Personal website. Retrieved 1/11/09.</ref> Her first novel, ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead'', won the 1997 [[Arthur Ellis Awards|Arthur Ellis Award]] for Best First Novel.<ref>[http://crimewriterscanada.com/cwc/pages/pastawards.html Arthur Ellis Award - list of past winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928140538/http://crimewriterscanada.com/cwc/pages/pastawards.html |date=2008-09-28 }}. Crime Writers of Canada. Retrieved 1/11/09.</ref>\n\nThe fictional [[hero]]ine in her novels, [[Temperance Brennan|Temperance \"Tempe\" Brennan]], is also a forensic anthropologist.  Her lifestyle closely mimics that of her creator,<ref name=\"birthday\">{{cite news| title =This much I know:Kathy Reichs, forensic anthropologist and writer, 60, London | work =Tom Templeton  | publisher =The Guardian | date =2008-10-26 | url =https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/oct/26/1 }}</ref><ref name=\"bookpage\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bookpage.com/9709bp/firstperson1.html |title=Meet this season's best discovery: Kathy Reichs |accessdate= 2008-11-16 |last=Mudge |first=Alden |date= September 1997 |publisher=Bookpage |archivedate=2008-06-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623094953/http://www.bookpage.com/9709bp/firstperson1.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> with Reichs stating that Brennan and she \"have the same CV\"<ref name=\"birthday\" /> and that \"Some of Tempe's personality traits are also mine\",<ref name= \"bookpage\" /> but there are differences in their personal lives such as the character's [[alcoholism]].<ref name=\"birthday\" />  A good portion of the novels are based on real life science, and Reichs has stated that she is \"fastidiously conscientious about getting the science right\".<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news| title =Kathy Reichs: The ice queen of crime | work =Peter Stanford | publisher =The Independent | date =2006-07-21 | url =https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/features/kathy-reichs-the-ice-queen-of-crime-408662.html }}</ref> She has used experience from her career in her novels, and said about ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead'' that \"Everything I describe in the book, I actually did\".<ref name=\"bookpage\" /> In the novel ''Grave Secrets'', she uses her experience from her visit to [[Guatemala]].<ref name= \"independent\" />\n\nShe has also written the [[young adult novel]]s series named ''[[Virals]]'' centered on Tempe's great-niece, Tory Brennan, and a pack of her friends Ben, Hiram, Shelton, and wolfdog Cooper.\n\nHer latest novel, ''Two Nights'', published July 11, 2017, features Sunday Night, a tough-talking, scarred heroine.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Two nights|last=Kathy|first=Reichs|isbn= 9781476726458|location=Toronto|oclc= 960987420|date = 2017-07-11}}</ref>\n\n===Temperance Brennan series===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!No.\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBNs\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n|''[[D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead]]''\n|1997\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-925518-9}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-449-83348-9}}\n|Won the 1997 [[Arthur Ellis Awards|Arthur Ellis Award]] for Best First Novel\n|-\n|2\n|''[[Death du Jour]]''\n|1999\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-925519-7}}<br />Hardcover: {{ISBNT|0-684-84118-5}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|0-754-05330-X}}\n|\n|-\n|3\n|''[[Deadly Decisions|Deadly D\u00e9cisions]]''\n|2000\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930710-3}}<br />Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-00820-6}}\n|\n|-\n|4\n|''[[Fatal Voyage]]''\n|2001\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930720-0}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-927-X}}\n|\n|-\n|5\n|''[[Grave Secrets]]''\n|2002\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-930730-8}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-928-8}}\n|\n|-\n|6\n|''[[Bare Bones (novel)|Bare Bones]]''\n|2003\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944147-0}}\n|\n|-\n|7\n|''[[Monday Mourning]]''\n|2004\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944148-9}}\n|\n|-\n|8\n|''[[Cross Bones (novel)|Cross Bones]]''\n|2005\n|Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-09-944149-7}}<br />Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01040-5}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|1-85686-985-7}}\n|\n|-\n|9\n|''[[Break No Bones]]''\n|2006\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01042-1}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|0-434-01544-X}}\n|\n|-\n|10\n|''[[Bones to Ashes]]''\n|2007\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434014620}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1416525653}}\n|\n|-\n|11\n|''[[Devil Bones]]''\n|2008\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0743294386}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1-4391-5440-3}}<br />Audio CD: {{ISBNT|978-1846571336}}\n|\n|-\n|12\n|''[[206 Bones]]''\n|2009\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0743294393}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0-4340-2005-8}}<br />\n|\n|-\n|13\n|''[[Spider Bones]]'' \n|2010\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-1439102398}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0-0995-5686-2}}<br />\n|released as ''Mortal Remains'' in UK and Australia in hardback,<br />reverted to ''Spider Bones'' for paperback release\n|-\n|14\n|''[[Flash and Bones]]''\n|2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1439102411}}\n|\n|-\n|15\n|''[[Bones are Forever]]''\n|2012\n|{{ISBNT|978-0434021130}}\n|\n|-\n|16\n|''[[Bones of the Lost]]'' \n|2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-1439102459}}\n|\n|-\n|17\n|''[[Bones Never Lie]]''\n|2014\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0345544018}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-0804194471}}\n|\n|-\n|18\n|''[[Speaking in Bones]]''\n| 2015\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434021192}}\n|\n|-\n|19\n| ''The Bone Collection''\n| 2016\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|9780606394642}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|9780399593222}}\n| A short story collection including ''First Bones'' (a prequel to ''D\u00e9j\u00e0 Dead''), ''Bones in her Pocket'', ''Swamp Bones'' and ''Bones on Ice''. These books have been numbered as 0.5, 15.5, 16.5, 17.5, respectively.<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28952915-the-bone-collection GoodReads]. GoodReads. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref>\n|-\n|20\n| ''A Conspiracy of Bones''\n| 2020\n|Hardback: {{ISBNT|9781785151187}}\n| \n|}\n\n===Stand-alone books===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!No.\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBNs\n!Notes\n|-\n|1\n| ''Two Nights''\n|2017\n| Hardback: {{ISBNT|978-0434021116}}<br />Paperback: {{ISBNT|978-1524755577}}\n| Stand-alone, \"off-series\" novel with new characters.<ref>[https://twitter.com/KathyReichs/status/803957093938167808 Twitter]. Twitter. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref><ref>[http://www.charlotteobserver.com/entertainment/books/reading-matters-blog/article111647727.html Website]. Website. Retrieved 2016/12/23.</ref>\n|}\n\n===Virals series===\n{{main|Virals}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!Title\n!Published\n!ISBN\n!Notes\n|-\n|''[[Virals (novel)|Virals]]''\n|2010\n|{{ISBNT|978-0099543947}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Seizure (Reichs novel)|Seizure]]''\n|2011\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595143945}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Code (Reichs novel)|Code]]''\n|2013\n|{{ISBNT|978-0099543855}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Exposure (Reichs novel)|Exposure]]''\n|2014\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595145307}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Terminal (Reichs novel)|Terminal]]''\n|2015\n|{{ISBNT|978-1595145284}}\n|\n|-\n|''[[Trace Evidence (Reichs novel)|Trace Evidence]]'' \n|2016\n|{{ISBNT|978-1784752392}}\n| a short story collection including ''Shock'', ''Shift'', ''Swipe'' and ''Spike'' (a new story set after the events of ''Terminal'').\n|-\n|}\n\n===Novellas===\nReichs has released six downloadable short stories:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n!Title\n!Published\n!Notes\n|-\n|''Shift''\n|2013\n| Set in the ''Virals'' country, but featuring both the Virals characters and Temperance Brennan.\n|-\n|''Bones In Her Pocket''\n|2013\n| A Temperance Brennan story giving details of a case briefly mentioned in ''Bones of the Lost''.\n|-\n|''Swipe''\n|2013\n| A ''Virals'' story, also featuring Temperance Brennan, set at Comic-Con in San Diego.\n|-\n|''Swamp Bones''\n|2014\n| A Temperance Brennan story set in the Florida Everglades.\n|-\n|''Shock''\n|2015\n| A ''Virals'' story telling how they first meet.\n|-\n|''Bones On Ice''\n|2015\n| A Temperance Brennan story of how she gets wrapped up in the ultimate cold case: a death on Mount Everest.\n|}\n\n== Television ==\n{{Main|Bones (TV series)}}\nThe 2005 [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] television series [[Bones (TV series)|''Bones'']] is inspired by Reichs' life and writing.<ref name=\"fox\">[http://www.fox.com/bones/showinfo/ Bones Show Info] {{webarchive|url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070923004209/http://www.fox.com/bones/showinfo/ |date=2007-09-23 }}</ref> The series borrows the name of the books' heroine, [[Temperance Brennan|Temperance \"Bones\" Brennan]].<ref name=\"yahoo\">{{Cite web |url=http://au.tv.yahoo.com/b/bones/549/kathy-reichs-20-things-you-need-to-know |title= Kathy Reichs: 20 Things You Need to Know |work=[[Yahoo!]] |publisher=Yahoo! Pty Limited |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080728010753/http://au.tv.yahoo.com/b/bones/549/kathy-reichs-20-things-you-need-to-know |archivedate=2008-07-28 |accessdate= 2008-11-16 }}</ref> As in the books, Brennan ([[Emily Deschanel]]) is a forensic anthropologist; however, there are many differences: the television character is younger, more socially awkward,<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> and is based in a fictionalized version of the [[Smithsonian Institution]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> Additionally, the TV-Brennan moonlights as an author,<ref name=\"fox\" /> writing about a fictional forensic anthropologist named Kathy Reichs.<ref>{{cite episode| title =Bodies in the Book | episodelink = | series =Bones | serieslink =Bones (TV series) | airdate =2007-10-14 | season =2 | number =15 }}</ref> Aside from the character name and occupation, there are few tie-ins between the TV show and the books.\n\nReichs works as a producer on the show to \"keep the science honest\".<ref name=\"yahoo\" /> She appeared in the second season episode \"Judas on a Pole\", playing Professor Constance Wright, a forensic anthropologist on the board conducting [[Zack Addy]]'s [[Dissertation#Examination|dissertation defense]].<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0915947/ ''Bones'' episode ''Judas on a Pole''] at IMDb.com</ref> She wrote the [[Bones (season 5)|Season Five]] episode \"The Witch in the Wardrobe\"<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1613910/fullcredits Full credits for ''Bones'' episode \"The Witch in the Wardrobe\"] at IMDb.com</ref> and the [[Bones (season 9)|Season Nine]] episode \"The Dude in the Dam\" and the [[Bones (season 11)|Season Eleven]] episode  \"The Stiff in the Cliff\" with her daughter Kerry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givememyremote.com/remote/2013/11/12/bones-recap-the-dude-in-the-dam/|title= BONES Recap: 'The Dude in the Dam'|work= givememyremote.com}}</ref>\n\n==Casey Anthony murder trial==\n{{Main|Death of Caylee Anthony}}\nIn 2011, Reichs was an expert witness in the [[Casey Anthony]] murder trial. After initially refusing to be a part of Anthony's defense, she cited biased media coverage as the reason she changed her mind.  \"Initially, I said no, and then I started seeing media coverage and it made me angry. This woman needed to be tried in court, not in the press.\"\n\nReichs performed a full skeletal analysis of Anthony's daughter, Caylee, but could not determine a cause of death.  She concluded that there was no evidence of abuse and that the child appeared to be well-nourished.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/books/news/story/2011-08-22/For-author-Kathy-Reichs-its-all-about-the-bones/50099182/1 | archiveurl= https://archive.is/20130412022818/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/books/news/story/2011-08-22/For-author-Kathy-Reichs-its-all-about-the-bones/50099182/1 | title= Reichs Examines Murder Victim Caylee Anthony | work= [[USA Today]]| archivedate= 12 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* \"Reichs, Kathy\", Britannica Online Encyclopedia, 2009, webpage: [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1377721/Kathy-Reichs EBc-KReichs].\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Kathy Reichs}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.kathyreichs.com}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20121210061409/http://www.jarrahloh.com/kathy-reichs/ Kathy Reichs: Turning a lifelong career into writing success] at Jarrah Loh.com\n*[http://www.shotsmag.co.uk/interview_view.aspx?interview_id=250 Kathy Reichs Interview Shots Ezine October 2012]\n\n{{Kathy Reichs}}\n{{Bones}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reichs, Kathy}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American forensic scientists]]\n[[Category:American academics]]\n[[Category:American mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Television producers from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Women television producers]]\n[[Category:American University alumni]]\n[[Category:Forensic anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women mystery writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Chicago]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Women forensic scientists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Women anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Bones (TV series)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:American women scientistsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kathy_Reichs"}
{"title_page": "Linda Saif", "text_new": "{{short description|American microbial scientist}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n| name = Linda Saif\n| image =  \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| othernames = \n| birth_name =         <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date =  \n| birth_place =  \n| death_date =  \n| death_place =  \n| death_cause = \n| residence = \n| era = \n| region = \n| workplaces =  Ohio State University\n| alma_mater =  [[College of Wooster]] (B.A. 1969)<br>[[Ohio State University]] (M.S. 1971, Ph.D. 1976)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vet.osu.edu/about-us/people/linda-saif|title=Linda Saif - College of Veterinary Medicine|website=vet.osu.edu}}</ref>\n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| school_tradition = \n| main_interests =  biologist\n| principal_ideas =virology, immunology\n| major_works = \n| awards = Wolf Prize in Agriculture\n| influences =  Dr. Edward Bohl<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.osu.edu/news/2003/05/05/saifnas/|title=Ohio State Researcher Elected To National Academy Of Sciences|date=5 May 2003|website=osu.edu}}</ref>\n| influenced = \n| spouse =  Mo Saif\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Linda J. Saif'''<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://cfaes.osu.edu/newsletter/cfaes-monthly/may-2017/linda-saif-elected-national-academy-inventors|title=Linda Saif elected to National Academy of Inventors - CFAES|website=cfaes.osu.edu}}</ref> is an American microbial scientist who works at [[Ohio State University]]. In 2015, she became the first female recipient of the [[Wolf Prize in Agriculture]] for her research in [[virology]] and [[immunology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Rivlin-Bennett-present-Israels-Nobel-Prize-to-eight-US-scientists-and-artists-404665|title=Rivlin, Bennett present 'Israel's Nobel Prize' to eight US scientists and artists|date=1 June 2015|website=[[Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oardc.ohio-state.edu/fahrp/newsview.asp?id=21114 |title=Linda Saif wins prestigious Wolf Prize in Agriculture |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=Food Animal Health Research Program, The Ohio State University |access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nSaif is a [[Fulbright program|Fulbright scholar]]<ref name=akron /> and a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nrc88.nas.edu/pnas_search/memberDetails.aspx?ctID=20002211|title=About the PNAS Member Editor|website=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref> In 2017 Saif was inducted into the [[National Academy of Inventors]] (NAI).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viroimmunelab.osu.edu/news/linda-saif-elected-national-academy-inventors|title=Linda Saif elected to National Academy of Inventors|last=|first=|date=April 2017|website=osu.edu|access-date=}}</ref> \nIn 2003, she studied the [[SARS coronavirus]] outbreak with the [[World Health Organization]].<ref name=akron>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131813197.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830102157/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131813197.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 August 2017 |title=Ohio scientists study animals to learn how to protect humans |last1=Wheeler |first1=Tracy |date=22 April 2005 |publisher=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] {{Subscription required|via=HighBeam}} |access-date=3 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nSaif is married to immunologist Dr. Mo Saif, Professor Emeritus, Department of Veterinary Preventive Medicine and Emeritus Program Head of the Food Animal Health Research Program, Ohio Agricultural Research and Development Center, The Ohio State University.<ref name=akron />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSaif grew up in Ohio and was exposed to agriculture from an early age from time spent at her grandparents' farm.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gPGZJ_YuMwgC&pg=PA832&lpg=PA832&dq=case+western+reserve+university+linda+saif#v=onepage&q=case%20western%20reserve%20university%20linda%20saif&f=false|title=American Women of Science Since 1900|last=Wayne|first=Tiffany K.|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598841589|language=en}}</ref> Saif attended private liberal arts college the [[College of Wooster]] in 1965 and graduated with a Honors in Biology in 1969. She briefly attended [[Case Western Reserve University]], before attending [[Ohio State University]] in 1970 to complete a Master of Science in Microbiology and Immunology. She then undertook a PhD at Ohio State University and completed in 1976.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wolf Prize in Agriculture}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saif, Linda}}\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Wolf Prize in Agriculture laureates]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:College of Wooster alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American microbial scientist}}\n{{Infobox scholar\n| name = Linda Saif\n| image =  \n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| fullname = \n| othernames = \n| birth_name =         <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date =  \n| birth_place =  \n| death_date =  \n| death_place =  \n| death_cause = \n| residence = \n| era = \n| region = \n| workplaces =  Ohio State University\n| alma_mater =  [[College of Wooster]] (B.A. 1969)<br>[[Ohio State University]] (M.S. 1971, Ph.D. 1976)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vet.osu.edu/about-us/people/linda-saif|title=Linda Saif - College of Veterinary Medicine|website=vet.osu.edu}}</ref>\n| thesis_title = \n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = \n| doctoral_advisor = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| school_tradition = \n| main_interests =  biologist\n| principal_ideas =virology, immunology\n| major_works = \n| awards = Wolf Prize in Agriculture\n| influences =  Dr. Edward Bohl<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.osu.edu/news/2003/05/05/saifnas/|title=Ohio State Researcher Elected To National Academy Of Sciences|date=5 May 2003|website=osu.edu}}</ref>\n| influenced = \n| spouse =  Mo Saif\n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Linda J. Saif'''<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://cfaes.osu.edu/newsletter/cfaes-monthly/may-2017/linda-saif-elected-national-academy-inventors|title=Linda Saif elected to National Academy of Inventors - CFAES|website=cfaes.osu.edu}}</ref> is an American microbial scientist who works at [[Ohio State University]]. In 2015, she became the first female recipient of the [[Wolf Prize in Agriculture]] for her research in [[virology]] and [[immunology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/Business-and-Innovation/Health-and-Science/Rivlin-Bennett-present-Israels-Nobel-Prize-to-eight-US-scientists-and-artists-404665|title=Rivlin, Bennett present 'Israel's Nobel Prize' to eight US scientists and artists|date=1 June 2015|website=[[Jerusalem Post]]|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oardc.ohio-state.edu/fahrp/newsview.asp?id=21114 |title=Linda Saif wins prestigious Wolf Prize in Agriculture |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=2015 |website=Food Animal Health Research Program, The Ohio State University |access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nSaif is a [[Fulbright program|Fulbright scholar]]<ref name=akron /> and a member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nrc88.nas.edu/pnas_search/memberDetails.aspx?ctID=20002211|title=About the PNAS Member Editor|website=[[National Academy of Sciences]]|access-date=3 November 2015}}</ref> In 2017 Saif was inducted into the [[National Academy of Inventors]] (NAI).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://viroimmunelab.osu.edu/news/linda-saif-elected-national-academy-inventors|title=Linda Saif elected to National Academy of Inventors|last=|first=|date=April 2017|website=osu.edu|access-date=}}</ref> \nIn 2003, she studied the [[SARS coronavirus]] outbreak with the [[World Health Organization]].<ref name=akron>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131813197.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830102157/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131813197.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 August 2017 |title=Ohio scientists study animals to learn how to protect humans |last1=Wheeler |first1=Tracy |date=22 April 2005 |publisher=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] {{Subscription required|via=HighBeam}} |access-date=3 November 2015 }}</ref>\n\nSaif is married to immunologist Dr. Mo Saif, Professor Emeritus, Department of Veterinary Preventive Medicine and Emeritus Program Head of the Food Animal Health Research Program, Ohio Agricultural Research and Development Center, The Ohio State University.<ref name=akron />\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSaif grew up in Ohio and was exposed to agriculture from an early age from time spent at her grandparents' farm.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=gPGZJ_YuMwgC&pg=PA832&lpg=PA832&dq=case+western+reserve+university+linda+saif#v=onepage&q=case%20western%20reserve%20university%20linda%20saif&f=false|title=American Women of Science Since 1900|last=Wayne|first=Tiffany K.|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598841589|language=en}}</ref> Saif attended private liberal arts college the [[College of Wooster]] in 1965 and graduated with a Honors in Biology in 1969. She briefly attended [[Case Western Reserve University]], before attending [[Ohio State University]] in 1970 to complete a Master of Science in Microbiology and Immunology. She then undertook a PhD at Ohio State University and completed in 1976.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wolf Prize in Agriculture}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saif, Linda}}\n[[Category:21st-century American biologists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women biologists]]\n[[Category:American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Wolf Prize in Agriculture laureates]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:College of Wooster alumni]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:American women scientistsusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linda_Saif"}
{"title_page": "Sandra Saouaf", "text_new": "{{short description|American immunologist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Sandra Saouaf\n| image         = Sandra Saouaf AWIS2011-38 crop.JPG\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by the blind and visually impaired's speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software  -->\n| caption       = Chemical Heritage Foundation, Philadelphia, PA, 2011\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people - supply only the year unless the exact date is already widely published, as per WP:DOB. For people that have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Sandra Jerrold-Jones, Sandra J. Saouaf\n| alma mater    = [[Rutgers College]]<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| occupation    = immunologist\n| employer     = [[Bristol-Myers Squibb]]<br>[[GlaxoSmithKline]]<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]]<br>Atlantic Bio Sci, LLC\n| years_active  = 1995-present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Sandra Saouaf''' is an American [[immunologist]] who researches [[autoimmune diseases]], such as [[rheumatoid arthritis]], [[Diabetes mellitus type 1|type 1 diabetes]], [[multiple sclerosis]] and others.\n\n==Biography==\nSandra Jerrold-Jones obtained a BA from [[Rutgers College]] in [[biology]] and went on to earn a PhD in Immunology from the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=bio>{{cite news|last1=Friedman|first1=Sally|title=Moorestown doctor on crusade against common disorders|url=http://www.courierpostonline.com/story/life/2014/07/07/doctor-crusade/12252351/|accessdate=25 November 2015|publisher=Courier Post|date=8 July 2014}}</ref> After completion of her degree, Saouaf went to work in the cell signaling laboratory of [[Bristol-Myers Squibb]]<ref name=timeline>{{cite web|title=Women in STEM: Professional Advice for High School Students|url=http://www.neumann.edu/about/news/news14-15/WomeninSTEM.asp|publisher=Neumann University|accessdate=25 November 2015|location=Aston, Pennsylvania|date=24 October 2014}}</ref>{{sfn|Gupta, et. al|2013|p=131}} where she completed her post doctorate fellowship.<ref name=Fellowship>{{cite web|title=Sandra Saouaf|url=http://www.connect6.com/Sandra-Saouaf/p/051214079187253159155008183177094011124233111049026166141123130223168129011232160125045195074107064208178004129025072215139185170033012237139014|publisher=Connect6|accessdate=25 November 2015}}</ref> She then worked briefly at [[GlaxoSmithKline]] before returning to the University of Pennsylvania.<ref name=timeline />  Saouaf left the university and began a consulting business with pharmaceutical and biotechnical companies,<ref name=timeline /> hoping to help speed the process of discoveries for drugs to treat autoimmune disease. In 2012, together with University of Pennsylvania colleagues, she \"discovered a possible treatment approach...through oral drugs\" and founded Atlantic Bio Sci, LLC.<ref name=bio /> In 2013, she won a Fellowship from the Alliance of Women Entrepreneurs.<ref name=trials>{{cite web|title=Meet Our 2013 Fellows|url=http://www.phillyawe.org/2013-fellows|publisher=Alliance of Women Entrepreneurs|accessdate=25 November 2015|location=Pottstown, Pennsylvania|date=2013}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Weiner |first1=D B|last2=Williams|first2=W V|last3=Siegel|first3=R M|last4=Jerrold-Jones|first4=S |display-authors=etal |date=January 1989|title=Molecular characterization of suppressor T cells|url= |journal=Transplantation Proceedings|volume=20|issue=6 |pages=1151\u20131153|doi= |pmid=2974197}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Siegel|first1=Richard M|last2=Katsumata|first2=Makoto|last3=Komori|first3=Shinji|last4=Jerrold-Jones|first4=Sandra |display-authors=etal |date=December 1990|title=Mechanisms of Autoimmunity in the Context of T-Cell Tolerance: Insights from Natural and Transgenic Animal Model Systems|journal=Immunological Reviews|volume=118|issue=1|pages=165\u2013192|doi=10.1111/j.1600-065X.1990.tb00816.x|pmid=2150401}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Saouaf|first1=Sandra J|last2=Mahajan|first2=Sandeep|last3=Rowley|first3=R Bruce|last4=Kut|first4=Stephanie A |display-authors=etal |date=September 1994|title=Temporal Differences in the Activation of Three Classes of Non-Transmembrane Protein Tyrosine Kinases Following B-Cell Antigen Receptor Surface Engagement|url= |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=91|issue=20|pages=9524\u20139528|doi= 10.1073/pnas.91.20.9524|pmid=7524079|pmc=44845|bibcode=1994PNAS...91.9524S}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Saouaf|first1=Sandra J|last2=Kut|first2=Stephanie A|last3=Fargnoli|first3=Joseph|last4=Rowley|first4=R Bruce |display-authors=etal |date=1995|title=Reconstitution of the B cell antigen receptor signaling components in COS cells|url= |journal=The Journal of Biological Chemistry|volume=270|issue=45|pages=27072\u20138|doi= 10.1074/jbc.270.45.27072|pmid=7592958|doi-access=free}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Saouaf|first1=Sandra J|last2=Brennan|first2=Patrick J|last3=Shen|first3=Yuan|last4=Greene|first4=Mark I.|date=December 2003|title=Mechanisms of peripheral immune tolerance: Conversion of the immune to the unresponsive phenotype|journal=Immunologic Research|volume=28|issue=3|pages=193\u2013199|doi= 10.1385/ir:28:3:193|pmid=14713714}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Iacono|first1=Kathryn T.|last2=Brown|first2=Amy L.|last3=Greene|first3=Mark I.|last4=Saouaf|first4= Sandra J.|date=December 2007|title=CD147 Immunoglobulin Superfamily Receptor Function and Role in Pathology|journal=Experimental and Molecular Pathology|volume=83|issue=3|pages=283\u2013295|doi=10.1016/j.yexmp.2007.08.014|pmid=17945211|pmc=2211739}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Saouaf|first1=Sandra J|last2=Brennan|first2=Patrick J|last3=Shen|first3=Yuan|last4=Greene|firs