{"title_page": "Sue Sherman-Broyles", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{short description|American researcher}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Sue Sherman-Broyles\n| thesis_title = Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in Arabidopsis\n| thesis_year = 2007\n| doctoral_advisor = [[June Nasrallah]]\n| alma_mater = [[Cornell University]] (Ph.D.)\n| workplaces = [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]]\n| residence = [[Cortland, New York]], U.S.\n| children = 2\n| spouse = [[Steven B. Broyles]]\n| other_names = Susan L. Sherman-Broyles\n}}\n\n'''Susan L. Sherman-Broyles''' is an American researcher. She is a research associate at [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nSherman-Broyles completed a doctor of philosophy at [[Cornell University]] in 2007. Her dissertation was titled \"Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in ''Arabidopsis''.\" Sherman-Broyle's doctoral advisor was [[June Nasrallah]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherman-Broyles|first=Susan L.|date=2007|title=Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in Arabidopsis|url=|journal=Cornell University, ProQuest Dissertations Publishing|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe is a research associate in the plant biology section at the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]] School of Integrative Science.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://cortlandfoundation.freeflowdp.com/cortlandfoundation/3929811351735215/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=8712&lm=1510974753000|title=A Son Named Cortland\u2026 and a Room Named Broyles|website=cortlandfoundation.freeflowdp.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> She works in [[Jeff J. Doyle]]'s laboratory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://plantbio.cals.cornell.edu/people/sue-sherman-broyles/|title=Sue Sherman-Broyles {{!}} Plant Biology Section|website=plantbio.cals.cornell.edu|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSherman-Broyles is married to [[Steven B. Broyles]], a professor of biology. They have two sons, Chris and Cortland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.cortland.edu/news/detail.dot?id=90d0bc3a-7373-474c-8eab-5cfb63b62656|title=No Green Needed to Green this Greenhouse - SUNY Cortland|website=www2.cortland.edu|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Cortland is named after CUNY Cortland, where his father was a professor.<ref name=\":0\" /> The couple resides in [[Cortland, New York]] {{As of|2012||df=|lc=|since=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://readme.readmedia.com/Steven-Broyles-Receives-Brooks-Dedicated-Teacher-Award/3840290|title=Steven Broyles Receives Brooks Dedicated Teacher Award|website=readme.readmedia.com|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n* {{Citation|last=Hamrick|first=J. L.|title=Factors influencing levels of genetic diversity in woody plant species|date=1992|work=Population Genetics of Forest Trees: Proceedings of the International Symposium on Population Genetics of Forest Trees Corvallis, Oregon, U.S.A., July 31\u2013August 2, 1990|volume=|pages=95\u2013124|editor-last=Adams|editor-first=W. T.|series=Forestry Sciences|publisher=Springer Netherlands|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-94-011-2815-5_7|isbn=9789401128155|last2=Godt|first2=Mary Jo W.|last3=Sherman-Broyles|first3=Susan L.|editor2-last=Strauss|editor2-first=Steven H.|editor3-last=Copes|editor3-first=Donald L.|editor4-last=Griffin|editor4-first=A. R.}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Pei|last2=Sherman-Broyles|first2=Susan|last3=Nasrallah|first3=Mikhail\u00a0E.|last4=Nasrallah|first4=June B.|date=2007|title=A Cryptic Modifier Causing Transient Self-Incompatibility in Arabidopsis thaliana|url=|journal=Current Biology|volume=17|issue=8|pages=734\u2013740|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2007.03.022|pmid=17412590|issn=0960-9822|pmc=1861850}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Nasrallah|first=June B.|last2=Nasrallah|first2=Mikhail E.|last3=Vrebalov|first3=Julia|last4=Liu|first4=Pei|last5=Farkas|first5=Agnes|last6=Boggs|first6=Nathan|last7=Sherman-Broyles|first7=Sue|date=2007|title=S Locus Genes and the Evolution of Self-Fertility in Arabidopsis thaliana|journal=The Plant Cell|language=en|volume=19|issue=1|pages=94\u2013106|doi=10.1105/tpc.106.048199|issn=1040-4651|pmid=17237349|pmc=1820967}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{google scholar id}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sherman-Broyles, Sue}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women]]\n[[Category:20th-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American scientists]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Cornell University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women scientists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=May 2019}}\n\n{{short description|American researcher}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Sue Sherman-Broyles\n| thesis_title = Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in Arabidopsis\n| thesis_year = 2007\n| doctoral_advisor = [[June Nasrallah]]\n| alma_mater = [[Cornell University]] (Ph.D.)\n| workplaces = [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]]\n| residence = [[Cortland, New York]], U.S.\n| children = 2\n| spouse = [[Steven B. Broyles]]\n| other_names = Susan L. Sherman-Broyles\n}}\n\n'''Susan L. Sherman-Broyles''' is an American researcher. She is a research associate at [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]].\n\n== Education and career ==\nSherman-Broyles completed a doctor of philosophy at [[Cornell University]] in 2007. Her dissertation was titled \"Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in ''Arabidopsis''.\" Sherman-Broyle's doctoral advisor was [[June Nasrallah]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sherman-Broyles|first=Susan L.|date=2007|title=Molecular evolution of the self -incompatibility locus in Arabidopsis|url=|journal=Cornell University, ProQuest Dissertations Publishing|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nShe is a research associate in the plant biology section at the [[Cornell University College of Agriculture and Life Sciences]] School of Integrative Science.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://cortlandfoundation.freeflowdp.com/cortlandfoundation/3929811351735215/MobilePagedArticle.action?articleId=8712&lm=1510974753000|title=A Son Named Cortland\u2026 and a Room Named Broyles|website=cortlandfoundation.freeflowdp.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> She works in [[Jeff J. Doyle]]'s laboratory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://plantbio.cals.cornell.edu/people/sue-sherman-broyles/|title=Sue Sherman-Broyles {{!}} Plant Biology Section|website=plantbio.cals.cornell.edu|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSherman-Broyles is married to [[Steven B. Broyles]], a professor of biology. They have two sons, Chris and Cortland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.cortland.edu/news/detail.dot?id=90d0bc3a-7373-474c-8eab-5cfb63b62656|title=No Green Needed to Green this Greenhouse - SUNY Cortland|website=www2.cortland.edu|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref> Cortland is named after CUNY Cortland, where his father was a professor.<ref name=\":0\" /> The couple resides in [[Cortland, New York]] {{As of|2012||df=|lc=|since=}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://readme.readmedia.com/Steven-Broyles-Receives-Brooks-Dedicated-Teacher-Award/3840290|title=Steven Broyles Receives Brooks Dedicated Teacher Award|website=readme.readmedia.com|access-date=2019-01-29}}</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n\n* {{Citation|last=Hamrick|first=J. L.|title=Factors influencing levels of genetic diversity in woody plant species|date=1992|work=Population Genetics of Forest Trees: Proceedings of the International Symposium on Population Genetics of Forest Trees Corvallis, Oregon, U.S.A., July 31\u2013August 2, 1990|volume=|pages=95\u2013124|editor-last=Adams|editor-first=W. T.|series=Forestry Sciences|pub